WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.150
&gt;&gt; Okay.
Thank you all for coming.

00:00:02.150 --> 00:00:05.450
Appreciate you being here.
It's my great pleasure to introduce George

00:00:05.450 --> 00:00:09.400
Steinmetz, I've been a big
fan of his work for some time.

00:00:09.400 --> 00:00:13.530
Amazing photographer and author of two books
now.

00:00:13.530 --> 00:00:16.630
And welcome, George.
Thanks for coming.

00:00:16.630 --> 00:00:17.630
&gt;&gt; [Applause]

00:00:17.630 --> 00:00:21.380
George Steinmetz: Thank you.
Umm, I wanted to show you all some pictures

00:00:21.380 --> 00:00:24.789
today from a long-term
project that I've been working on about the

00:00:24.789 --> 00:00:30.300
world's deserts and I got
into this because when I was a young man and

00:00:30.300 --> 00:00:32.730
I hitchhiked across the
Sahara Desert and I imagined what it would

00:00:32.730 --> 00:00:34.890
be like to fly over the
desert.

00:00:34.890 --> 00:00:38.290
And about 12 years ago I talked National Geographic
into doing a big

00:00:38.290 --> 00:00:42.761
project in the Sahara and I wanted to aerial
photos and I got

00:00:42.761 --> 00:00:46.649
into motorized paragliding to do that.
And when I was flying over the Sahara on that

00:00:46.649 --> 00:00:50.990
first trip it opened up
my mind to a new way of seeing the world from

00:00:50.990 --> 00:00:53.489
the air.
And I started to wonder what it would be like

00:00:53.489 --> 00:00:56.700
if I took my crazy
little aircraft to different parts of the

00:00:56.700 --> 00:01:01.899
world, umm, to other
deserts, to the Atacama, to the Gobi, to Antarctica,

00:01:01.899 --> 00:01:04.270
which most people
don't think of as a desert but it is.

00:01:04.270 --> 00:01:08.170
It's the world's largest desert.
And what I'm gonna show you are pictures from

00:01:08.170 --> 00:01:13.380
that project and then in
the past six years I've actually been using

00:01:13.380 --> 00:01:16.170
Google Earth a lot for my
research and trying figure out where to go

00:01:16.170 --> 00:01:19.159
'cause I go to very remote
areas where there's -- most of these areas

00:01:19.159 --> 00:01:21.120
have never really been
photographed before.

00:01:21.120 --> 00:01:23.549
And so it's, uh, you have to find your subject
matter and it's very

00:01:23.549 --> 00:01:26.939
difficult and expensive to get around so you
need to know where you're

00:01:26.939 --> 00:01:30.560
going.
They call this project hyper-arid because

00:01:30.560 --> 00:01:33.920
the areas we've been going
to are the driest areas on our planet.

00:01:33.920 --> 00:01:36.520
They all get less than 10 centimeters of annual
percipitation.

00:01:36.520 --> 00:01:42.909
This is in the dry valleys of Antarctica.
These are Victoria Dunes.

00:01:42.909 --> 00:01:45.840
I was down there on a grant from the National
Science Foundation to

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:52.790
document their scientific research work there.
This is in the, umm, Atacama Desert on the

00:01:52.790 --> 00:02:00.189
coast of Peru.
That's the Pacific in the background.

00:02:00.189 --> 00:02:04.689
And, uh, this is up in the, umm, Qaidam Basin
in China on kind of the

00:02:04.689 --> 00:02:09.050
backside of the Himalaya, the north side of
the Himalaya.

00:02:09.050 --> 00:02:17.440
Uh, it's in the Gobi Desert in China.
These are the Badain Jaran Desert in -- these

00:02:17.440 --> 00:02:19.000
are the tallest dunes in
the world.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:22.450
They're over 1200 feet.
These are the sub dunes that are part of the

00:02:22.450 --> 00:02:29.069
1200-foot dunes.
And this is in the Namib Desert in Namibia

00:02:29.069 --> 00:02:35.540
southwest Africa.
And this is in Antarctica, also.

00:02:35.540 --> 00:02:39.540
This is in the Dry Valleys.
This frozen lake is the purest water in the

00:02:39.540 --> 00:02:48.300
world.
Umm, and this is out in the Empty Quarters

00:02:48.300 --> 00:02:52.129
of Arabia.
Umm, the tracks on the right are the -- are

00:02:52.129 --> 00:02:55.160
my car tracks and the
car -- car -- tracks on the left are 50 years

00:02:55.160 --> 00:02:59.099
old.
The area is so sterile it's paralyzed landscape.

00:02:59.099 --> 00:03:03.180
There's really no -- there's no life out there
at all.

00:03:03.180 --> 00:03:06.430
And this is where the Empty Quarter bumps
into the United Arab

00:03:06.430 --> 00:03:10.920
Emirates and this is a -- they tried to stabilize
the sand with

00:03:10.920 --> 00:03:14.340
pumping ground water into a little drip irrigation
system.

00:03:14.340 --> 00:03:22.050
This is the last steam train in the Gobi Desert
with a similar sand

00:03:22.050 --> 00:03:32.239
stabilization program.
And this is in the -- this is the village

00:03:32.239 --> 00:03:33.680
of Rendille people in
northern Kenya.

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:37.610
The area's now going through a severe draught
and the people have

00:03:37.610 --> 00:03:41.150
moved to a mission post to get education,
access to water, and medical

00:03:41.150 --> 00:03:44.620
care, but when they're in a sedentary village
environment they can't

00:03:44.620 --> 00:03:48.400
feed their camels and their goats so this
is kind of their village and

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:55.160
town but most of their adult males and the
livestock was 10 to 15-miles

00:03:55.160 --> 00:04:02.770
away trying to find grass for their animals.
And this caravan's carrying salt across the

00:04:02.770 --> 00:04:04.560
Sahara.
Still do that.

00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:09.030
This picture's about ten years old but they
still do.

00:04:09.030 --> 00:04:15.159
This is in Iran.
These -- the holes are from underground aquaducts

00:04:15.159 --> 00:04:16.410
that are thousands
of years old.

00:04:16.410 --> 00:04:21.570
They have vertical shafts to clean them out
and they have to go down

00:04:21.570 --> 00:04:25.330
every ten years or so to take out the mineralization
out of the canals

00:04:25.330 --> 00:04:29.980
that take water from the highlands down to
the lowland farms.

00:04:29.980 --> 00:04:37.160
This is a similar system in China.
The -- this Qanat system, the system of underground

00:04:37.160 --> 00:04:39.990
irrigation spread
along the silk road from Iran all the way

00:04:39.990 --> 00:04:44.660
to western
China and then you can find it on the other

00:04:44.660 --> 00:04:47.600
side of the world in
Moracco.

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:54.011
World travel -- knowledge traveled by camel.
Umm, this is the road to the oil fields in

00:04:54.011 --> 00:04:55.250
China, the Taklamakan
Desert.

00:04:55.250 --> 00:05:00.729
You get a similar system of taking salty ground
water and putting it

00:05:00.729 --> 00:05:04.930
through dip irrigation to make plants to stabilize
the dunes so that

00:05:04.930 --> 00:05:08.930
the road doesn't get overtaken by dunes.
And the little blue house is for the person

00:05:08.930 --> 00:05:12.220
who makes sure the drip
irrigation pipes don't leak.

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:19.690
This is the lowest point in China.
It's about 50 meters below sea level in the

00:05:19.690 --> 00:05:25.820
Taklamakan in the tar pit --
And these pits are used to harvest salt.

00:05:25.820 --> 00:05:34.490
These -- there's some prison labor out there.
Umm, that's harvesting peppers on the floor

00:05:34.490 --> 00:05:45.449
of the Taklamakan Desert.
Put 'em out to dry.

00:05:45.449 --> 00:05:49.389
And this is, umm, an area where they cultivate
salt in the Sahara.

00:05:49.389 --> 00:05:53.389
It's for animals -- animal use.
And the different colors are because of the

00:05:53.389 --> 00:05:55.250
mineral content of the --
of the mud.

00:05:55.250 --> 00:06:00.449
They mix kind of salty mud with well water
and then they -- the -- the

00:06:00.449 --> 00:06:06.990
white areas you see like, umm, that's from
salt forming on the surface

00:06:06.990 --> 00:06:10.949
kind of like, umm, like ice forming on the
surface of a pond and they

00:06:10.949 --> 00:06:12.509
splash the water up and then the ice -- sorry,
the salt will go down

00:06:12.509 --> 00:06:18.340
to the bottom and after a month or so of this
process the whole basin will be filled enough

00:06:18.340 --> 00:06:23.750
with salt they can scrape it out in their
little

00:06:23.750 --> 00:06:27.280
mud-lined basins.
Umm, this is in, uh, central Sahara.

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:33.270
This is in northern Mali.
And there's a different salt trade from, uh,

00:06:33.270 --> 00:06:37.860
some oases between Mali
and Algeria and they carry it down by camel

00:06:37.860 --> 00:06:43.160
caravan to Timbuktu and
this is the only, umm, uh, the only, uh, consistent

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:45.620
water point so
there's a little village here where they trade

00:06:45.620 --> 00:06:48.789
water for salt and the
village is half buried in the sand.

00:06:48.789 --> 00:06:51.422
And there's no vegetation at all because the
camels have eaten

00:06:51.422 --> 00:06:52.422
everything.
You go 10 miles away from the village and

00:06:52.422 --> 00:06:58.199
you would find scrub
vegetation but within 10 miles it's all been

00:06:58.199 --> 00:07:03.361
eaten by camel.
Inside of the Empty Quarter of Arabia.

00:07:03.361 --> 00:07:12.910
Very unusual to have two colors of sand.
You have to have very strong winds.

00:07:12.910 --> 00:07:17.669
Umm, and, uh, these are, umm, James's flamingos
in Bolivia.

00:07:17.669 --> 00:07:24.180
And these are greater flamingos.
This is in Iran.

00:07:24.180 --> 00:07:30.280
Flamingos are very skiddish birds but with
my aircraft I can get

00:07:30.280 --> 00:07:33.540
fairly close to them.
Camels going out to get fodder on the Empty

00:07:33.540 --> 00:07:37.009
Quarter of Arabia.
It's funny.

00:07:37.009 --> 00:07:43.620
I started -- this picture went viral on the
internet about two years

00:07:43.620 --> 00:07:46.830
ago and I started getting these strange e-mails
from people in the

00:07:46.830 --> 00:07:50.910
Middle East. They thought it was taken with
a predator aircraft and

00:07:50.910 --> 00:07:53.919
then they wanted to make sure it was -- they
thought it was, you know,

00:07:53.919 --> 00:07:55.889
was I part of the CIA and how did I get this
picture?

00:07:55.889 --> 00:07:57.110
And then I started getting e-mails from camera
clubs in the U.S.

00:07:57.110 --> 00:07:58.820
because they wanted to know what camera lens
I took and it was just

00:07:58.820 --> 00:07:59.820
funny.

00:07:59.820 --> 00:08:00.820
&gt;&gt; [Laughing]

00:08:00.820 --> 00:08:01.820
George Steinmetz: Different sides of the same
coin.

00:08:01.820 --> 00:08:07.460
They all thought it was done in Photoshop,
too.

00:08:07.460 --> 00:08:14.520
The central Sahara.
It's in northern Chad.

00:08:14.520 --> 00:08:19.630
And this is in, uh, Namib Desert in the southwest
coast of Africa.

00:08:19.630 --> 00:08:29.699
And zebras on a nature reserve in Namibia.
