not really understood.

00:08:32.779 --> 00:08:36.330
There's, umm, these kind of bald areas and
they suspect that it could

00:08:36.330 --> 00:08:41.880
be some kind of toxic in the ground, maybe
an insect colony, like an

00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:45.210
ant hill, the ants left some sort of toxicity,
or some kind of tree that

00:08:45.210 --> 00:08:50.350
no longer exists that left some toxicity in
a decayed root system but

00:08:50.350 --> 00:08:57.040
nobody really understands.
This is the, umm, end of the Colorado River

00:08:57.040 --> 00:08:59.740
where it hits the Gulf of
California and Mexico.

00:08:59.740 --> 00:09:05.170
Down river from calexico and you have 30-foot
tides here.

00:09:05.170 --> 00:09:10.580
So this was taken in the morning of a full
moon when the tide was at

00:09:10.580 --> 00:09:13.660
its lowest.
Used to be one of the most productive wetlands

00:09:13.660 --> 00:09:19.940
in North America and
now it's just a sand desert raked by tide.

00:09:19.940 --> 00:09:24.160
This is the Altiplano in Bolivia.
This lake is the biggest salt flat in the

00:09:24.160 --> 00:09:28.600
world.
It's, umm, 12,000 feet.

00:09:28.600 --> 00:09:34.380
And in the springtime it gets flooded.
Those are two cars -- my two cars -- the two

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:38.920
cars I hired take aroung and we use one for
the aircraft and one for camp supplies but

00:09:38.920 --> 00:09:44.590
I wanted them for
scale to get an idea how big the Sahara was.

00:09:44.590 --> 00:09:47.190
This is taken just after sunrise.
And this is also in the Altiplano.

00:09:47.190 --> 00:09:54.080
This lake's about 14,000 feet.
Laguna Co -- Laguna Colorada with a indemnic

00:09:54.080 --> 00:09:57.310
species of flamingo that
nest there, James's Flamingo.

00:09:57.310 --> 00:10:06.790
This is Cape Vercillos on the southeast African
coast -- southwest African coast

00:10:06.790 --> 00:10:10.860
in Namibia.
Most of the areas I go to there are virtually

00:10:10.860 --> 00:10:13.600
no people there.
