You kinda swing like you're in a playground
swing.

00:35:53.430 --> 00:35:57.300
You get turbulence.
It's self-stabilizing so I can take pictures

00:35:57.300 --> 00:36:01.010
with my hands off the
controls.

00:36:01.010 --> 00:36:04.089
&gt;&gt; Sorry.
I'm relaying some questions from the San Francisco

00:36:04.089 --> 00:36:05.089
office.

00:36:05.089 --> 00:36:06.099
George Steinmetz: Okay.

00:36:06.099 --> 00:36:09.820
&gt;&gt; And, uh, let's see.
So the question number one is, have you done

00:36:09.820 --> 00:36:12.940
many shots from this
elevated angle before the series?

00:36:12.940 --> 00:36:16.200
What made you want to take them all from this
perspective?

00:36:16.200 --> 00:36:20.060
And then the third one is, how did the new
perspective change the way

00:36:20.060 --> 00:36:23.589
you would frame photos?
Did it influence your style on the ground?

00:36:23.589 --> 00:36:26.910
George Steinmetz: Umm, I've always liked taking
pictures from above

00:36:26.910 --> 00:36:28.310
even, like, when I was a young guy traveling
in Africa.

00:36:28.310 --> 00:36:33.100
Always wanted to climb a tree to take a picture.
Always liked kind of the elevated perspective.

00:36:33.100 --> 00:36:37.150
But this aircraft it gives me kind of what
I think is kind of a

00:36:37.150 --> 00:36:40.089
missing altitude, if there is such a thing,
in aerial photos.

00:36:40.089 --> 00:36:44.060
Most people's aerial photos are very high
and, umm, usually like when

00:36:44.060 --> 00:36:46.380
you're taking off in a plane like the really
cool view is when you're

00:36:46.380 --> 00:36:49.000
just about to land.
And that's the kind of altitude I like to

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:53.030
fly in where it's, umm, you
get kind of a three dimensional quality to

00:36:53.030 --> 00:36:57.410
the landscape, especially if you use a wide-angle
lens you can get a human sense of scale, you

00:36:57.410 --> 00:37:00.160
can see,
you know, the vertical surfaces but you can

00:37:00.160 --> 00:37:01.790
also see the horizontal
surfaces.

00:37:01.790 --> 00:37:06.720
And I find it's just a much more interesting
space to be in.

00:37:06.720 --> 00:37:09.770
I can get an aerial view where you can get
a sense of scale and human

00:37:09.770 --> 00:37:16.130
perspective, umm, so, uh, and I -- it's a
problem for me when I go in

00:37:16.130 --> 00:37:18.980
the field with my aircraft 'cause I tend to
wanna go flying every day.

00:37:18.980 --> 00:37:22.530
It's fun to fly but it's also it's very expensive
to bring my rig over

00:37:22.530 --> 00:37:24.980
there, and have the cars and all the support,
and I usually have these

00:37:24.980 --> 00:37:27.460
French guys who wake up every morning and
they wanna go flying.

00:37:27.460 --> 00:37:31.720
So it does influence my -- my work in that
I tend to take a lot more

00:37:31.720 --> 00:37:34.640
aerial photos when I go out in the field with
my aircraft.

00:37:34.640 --> 00:37:38.930
But when I'm working on the ground it's same
old same old.

00:37:38.930 --> 00:37:45.390
&gt;&gt; I had a quick question about the logistics.
So you're talking about how you look for a

00:37:45.390 --> 00:37:47.090
while on Google Earth and
you find a spot --

00:37:47.090 --> 00:37:48.090
George Steinmetz: Yeah.

00:37:48.090 --> 00:37:52.880
&gt;&gt; -- And just it seems -- it seems like in
all the photos that we saw

00:37:52.880 --> 00:37:54.770
that would take a lifetime and a half to get
out there, seeing how the cars are so small.

00:37:54.770 --> 00:37:58.099
What sort of considerations?
I mean, you find a spot you wanna take a photo

00:37:58.099 --> 00:38:01.339
of and then do you
personally go from there to seeing if it's

00:38:01.339 --> 00:38:06.400
accessible and seeing if it's
flyable like you're not in the lead of a big

00:38:06.400 --> 00:38:07.400
mountain?

00:38:07.400 --> 00:38:09.810
George Steinmetz: Generally like in a place
like the Empty Quarter a

00:38:09.810 --> 00:38:13.930
big issue is could you get there?
And you go -- you can go at it a couple ways

00:38:13.930 --> 00:38:15.360
you can go and say, you
know, what's easy to get to?

00:38:15.360 --> 00:38:17.880
And you get to it and you look there.
But generally it's like going through the

00:38:17.880 --> 00:38:21.400
lawn with a magnifying glass
and I'll try to find cool stuff and then say,

00:38:21.400 --> 00:38:22.900
jeez, how can I get
there?

00:38:22.900 --> 00:38:25.190
And sometimes you don't really know.
It's hard to know with what you're seeing

00:38:25.190 --> 00:38:26.711
Google Earth what the
terrain is like.

00:38:26.711 --> 00:38:30.829
Like the area in Saudi Arabia where you see
these enormous dunes that

00:38:30.829 --> 00:38:33.260
are shaped like an egg crate and then the
salt flats you just don't

00:38:33.260 --> 00:38:36.341
know if that's drivable.
And there's nobody to call to find out if

00:38:36.341 --> 00:38:38.310
it's drivable.
And you go to Saudi Arabia and the locals

00:38:38.310 --> 00:38:39.760
have never been out there
'cause you're the crazy son of a gun who wants

00:38:39.760 --> 00:38:42.380
to go out there.
And they don't wanna go out there.

00:38:42.380 --> 00:38:46.510
So there's a lot of issues.
In Libya we wanted to go out into the big

00:38:46.510 --> 00:38:48.940
dune fields and we had a
driver that would come up with every excuse

00:38:48.940 --> 00:38:51.650
not to go out there.
And finally I said, look, we're going out

00:38:51.650 --> 00:38:53.020
there, dude.
And he got down and prayed.

00:38:53.020 --> 00:38:54.859
This guy was not a very religious guy and
he was praying.

00:38:54.859 --> 00:38:55.859
&gt;&gt; [Laughing]

00:38:55.859 --> 00:38:57.070
George Steinmetz: And he was sure that he
was gonna die out there.

00:38:57.070 --> 00:38:59.190
We got out there and look, there are tracks,
there are wrecked cars,

00:38:59.190 --> 00:39:01.980
it's okay.
And he was still you know you know, he was

00:39:01.980 --> 00:39:05.440
really nervous.
And so there are a lot of issues, political

00:39:05.440 --> 00:39:09.040
issues, like permits and
when I wanted to go out into the salt deserts

00:39:09.040 --> 00:39:14.079
in Iran, I had to get a
13-car escort from the Iranian military police

00:39:14.079 --> 00:39:17.070
that are supposed to be
chasing after heroin smugglers and to have

00:39:17.070 --> 00:39:21.700
13 cars and get a colonel
up there to protect the crazy American guy.

00:39:21.700 --> 00:39:24.780
I mean, it's amazing that they let me out
there at all let alone to

00:39:24.780 --> 00:39:28.054
give me a 13-car military escort, but I had
to organize all that to get

00:39:28.054 --> 00:39:30.940
out to a place that I thought would be really
cool from Google Earth.

00:39:30.940 --> 00:39:33.640
So you have all these different problems you
gotta worry -- and then,

00:39:33.640 --> 00:39:38.420
like, wind conditions, and getting stuck in
the mud, and carburetors breaking and all

00:39:38.420 --> 00:39:42.069
that other stuff.
Umm, and for some of the countries it's just

00:39:42.069 --> 00:39:43.950
 -- I mean, getting into
Libya or Iran, or -- it's really tough.

00:39:43.950 --> 00:39:48.180
I'm going to Algeria next week.
Getting permission to fly aircraft like mine

00:39:48.180 --> 00:39:50.300
in Algeria is not a
straightforward process.

00:39:50.300 --> 00:39:53.030
It's a very non-linear process.

00:39:53.030 --> 00:39:54.030
&gt;&gt; [Laughing]

00:39:54.030 --> 00:39:56.020
George Steinmetz: Yes?

00:39:56.020 --> 00:39:59.330
&gt;&gt; I'm just wondering so where would you like
to go?

00:39:59.330 --> 00:40:01.841
Like what's your plans?
I didn't see Australia there.

00:40:01.841 --> 00:40:06.440
Or what countries can't you go 'cause it's
too dangerous or it's too

00:40:06.440 --> 00:40:07.440
hard to get into?

00:40:07.440 --> 00:40:10.190
George Steinmetz: Well, I -- when I started
this project I looked at

00:40:10.190 --> 00:40:13.830
some kind of old textbooks about deserts and
I got some maps and I

00:40:13.830 --> 00:40:17.940
figured out all the different places that
I had to go to finish my project.

00:40:17.940 --> 00:40:21.609
And right now my list I've got Algeria, which
I'm going next week, and

00:40:21.609 --> 00:40:25.150
Egypt which is also very difficult for permission
to fly like flying

00:40:25.150 --> 00:40:28.670
over the pyramids.
Not so easy to get permission.

00:40:28.670 --> 00:40:30.650
And I need to go to Eritrea in Ethiopia and
then I'm pretty much

00:40:30.650 --> 00:40:32.000
done.
I didn't go to Australia 'cause it's not dry

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:34.230
enough.
It gets more than ten centimeters and if you're

00:40:34.230 --> 00:40:38.589
gonna be strict to the
rule hyper-arid it's too wet down there.

00:40:38.589 --> 00:40:41.579
They get monsoonal rains and it's very dry
for most of the year but

00:40:41.579 --> 00:40:43.569
when it rains they get hosed and it doesn't
really fit.

00:40:43.569 --> 00:40:49.260
It's beautiful but it doesn't really fit.
Antarctica fits but Australia it's not on

00:40:49.260 --> 00:40:51.710
the menu.

00:40:51.710 --> 00:40:55.180
&gt;&gt; I was wondering if there was any sort of
magic that allows -- that

00:40:55.180 --> 00:40:59.130
you use to be able to get to fly in these
places.

00:40:59.130 --> 00:41:02.319
I mean, I'm a pilot.
I would love to fly some of these places.

00:41:02.319 --> 00:41:05.819
Do you have to be with National Geographic
is that the magic ticket

00:41:05.819 --> 00:41:07.970
or just lots of hard work?

00:41:07.970 --> 00:41:10.510
George Steinmetz: There's nobody from National
Geographic here so I

00:41:10.510 --> 00:41:12.800
can say honestly they don't really help at
all.

00:41:12.800 --> 00:41:15.260
They -- they fund -- they fund -- they pay
for it which is wonderful

00:41:15.260 --> 00:41:18.640
but in terms of access generally that's got
to be worked out.

00:41:18.640 --> 00:41:22.190
I gotta work -- that's my problem.
Like going to Libya, I smuggle my aircraft

00:41:22.190 --> 00:41:24.380
in and I had to work all
that stuff out.

00:41:24.380 --> 00:41:27.880
And so, umm, and most of these places I mean,
they've never -- they

00:41:27.880 --> 00:41:31.820
never heard of National Geographic.

00:41:31.820 --> 00:41:35.540
&gt;&gt; So it's all -- this is your personal expertise?
You've slowly figured it out place by place?

00:41:35.540 --> 00:41:37.510
George Steinmetz: Yeah.
It's like that's my cross to bear.

00:41:37.510 --> 00:41:38.510
&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:41:38.510 --> 00:41:39.900
George Steinmetz: Yeah. I mean, I love the
Geographic and

00:41:39.900 --> 00:41:43.050
that -- you know, they publish the work and
they support it but they

00:41:43.050 --> 00:41:48.579
don't know how to get an aircraft into Yemen.
They don't have to do it.

00:41:48.579 --> 00:41:49.579
It's not their thing.

00:41:49.579 --> 00:41:50.579
&gt;&gt; [Laughing]

00:41:50.579 --> 00:41:51.579
&gt;&gt; Thanks.

00:41:51.579 --> 00:41:52.660
George Steinmetz: They'll send me a letter
and I can use their

00:41:52.660 --> 00:41:53.701
stationary but that's about it.

00:41:53.701 --> 00:41:57.930
&gt;&gt; I'm just curious.
Which do you usually find is easier to get,

00:41:57.930 --> 00:41:58.930
permission or forgiveness?

00:41:58.930 --> 00:41:59.930
&gt;&gt; [Laughing]

00:41:59.930 --> 00:42:02.100
George Steinmetz: It's a lot easier to get
forgiveness.

00:42:02.100 --> 00:42:05.890
There's a serious question because you have
to figure out, you know,

00:42:05.890 --> 00:42:09.380
how to play the game and, like, in some African
buearacracy you try

00:42:09.380 --> 00:42:12.450
and get permission and you're looking for
a world of pain.

00:42:12.450 --> 00:42:16.079
And you just go out there and some guy might
get upset and, you know,

00:42:16.079 --> 00:42:18.750
you give him like a case of beer out of the
back of the car and

00:42:18.750 --> 00:42:19.750
everything's okay.

00:42:19.750 --> 00:42:20.750
&gt;&gt; [Laughing]

00:42:20.750 --> 00:42:23.260
George Steinmetz: It's hard to know how to
play that and in North

00:42:23.260 --> 00:42:26.410
Africa it's really different because you're
between the European

00:42:26.410 --> 00:42:32.510
buearacracy and kinda the free-living way
of Africa and so you kinda get the worst of

00:42:32.510 --> 00:42:41.380
both worlds.
And I'm gonna find out more next week.

00:42:41.380 --> 00:42:43.880
&gt;&gt; Hi, thanks for showing us very greatful
photos.

00:42:43.880 --> 00:42:47.380
Can you tell us what kind of camera you use?

00:42:47.380 --> 00:42:51.040
George Steinmetz: Yeah.
I try to keep it pretty simple while I'm flying

00:42:51.040 --> 00:42:53.880
because it's awkward
changing lenses.

00:42:53.880 --> 00:42:56.410
You get dust in 'em and stuff because I'm
in a very dusty environment

00:42:56.410 --> 00:42:59.280
but you don't wanna be taking your hands off
the controls and have,

00:42:59.280 --> 00:43:04.079
like -- there's no place to put anything.
It's basically like a flying lawn chair.

00:43:04.079 --> 00:43:09.000
So, umm, I keep it real simple.
I usually have one body, sometimes two extra

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:12.630
lenses -- usually it's
one extra lens -- and I switched about five

00:43:12.630 --> 00:43:16.339
years ago from film to
digital and that made my life a lot easier,

00:43:16.339 --> 00:43:20.670
umm, because I can have
big CF cards so I don't have to change cassettes

00:43:20.670 --> 00:43:24.540
in flight.
And, umm, the -- with digital imaging I can

00:43:24.540 --> 00:43:30.640
use high ASA without any
loss of quality so I can take pictures in

00:43:30.640 --> 00:43:33.290
really low light and I used
to have problems to use really fast lenses

00:43:33.290 --> 00:43:37.300
and focusing it accurately
and now I can be kinda the pig and use autofocus

00:43:37.300 --> 00:43:41.710
and I don't really
shoot like that but it's gotten a lot easier.

00:43:41.710 --> 00:43:45.369
And the resolution is so much better.
I can get -- I can take pictures up and blow

00:43:45.369 --> 00:43:49.021
them up the size of the
screen and they're just tack sharp and in

00:43:49.021 --> 00:43:51.589
film they start to fall
apart once you get them much bigger than that.

00:43:51.589 --> 00:43:56.670
So it's made life a lot easier.

00:43:56.670 --> 00:43:59.940
&gt;&gt; So, one more question for the few pilot
and paraglider pilot geeks

00:43:59.940 --> 00:44:03.359
in the audience.
Umm, you show up at this place and, I mean,

00:44:03.359 --> 00:44:04.900
how much do you know about
the meteorology?

00:44:04.900 --> 00:44:09.170
How much do you know about the conditions,
and are there local pilots

00:44:09.170 --> 00:44:13.530
to show you if it's safe to fly and -- and
how do you --

00:44:13.530 --> 00:44:14.920
George Steinmetz: No.No.
You're kind of going into virgin turf every

00:44:14.920 --> 00:44:17.740
time and there aren't
no -- there aren't any local guides.

00:44:17.740 --> 00:44:22.920
I mean, sometimes I'll go and maybe in a couple
South American

00:44:22.920 --> 00:44:25.630
countries you can find somebody but generally
you're -- you're kinda

00:44:25.630 --> 00:44:28.950
figuring it out on your own. And you can talk
to -- try and find guides

00:44:28.950 --> 00:44:33.660
and say, you know, what are the winds like?
I've been going to the Sahara -- the Sahara's

00:44:33.660 --> 00:44:36.290
divided into about ten
different countries and the only real season

00:44:36.290 --> 00:44:40.750
for flying there is in
the fall because in the winter they get -- after

00:44:40.750 --> 00:44:43.260
February/March they
get ripping winds, Harmattan winds that carve

00:44:43.260 --> 00:44:45.650
the landsape if you look
at satellite imagery.

00:44:45.650 --> 00:44:48.369
So there's really no -- only one season.
I got two or three months.

00:44:48.369 --> 00:44:51.431
So I've missed my kids' birthdays every year
for ten years 'cause they're -- all

00:44:51.431 --> 00:44:59.630
the birthdays are in the fall and I'm just,
sorry, Daddy's gone to the

00:44:59.630 --> 00:45:00.630
Sahara.
That's the way it is.

00:45:00.630 --> 00:45:01.630
It's the season.
It's like the surf's up and I gotta go.

00:45:01.630 --> 00:45:02.770
But it's a real problem.
You try and ask -- you go to a place like

00:45:02.770 --> 00:45:05.240
the Empty Quarter you try and
ask 'cause you look at this landscape and

00:45:05.240 --> 00:45:07.839
you can see they've got huge
winds.

00:45:07.839 --> 00:45:10.910
I can tell by looking at the dunes.
I know what direction they're coming from.

00:45:10.910 --> 00:45:13.161
I just don't know what time of year they might
be down and to get

00:45:13.161 --> 00:45:16.130
around up there safely you have to be there
when the temperatures are

00:45:16.130 --> 00:45:18.570
relatively cool so that the cars don't overheat
so you don't have to

00:45:18.570 --> 00:45:23.660
carry literally a ton of water.
And so if you go down you can walk outta there.

00:45:23.660 --> 00:45:27.930
So you wanna be down in the winter in, uh,
a stable atmosphere.

00:45:27.930 --> 00:45:31.730
But it's very hard to -- there aren't any
meteorological stations out

00:45:31.730 --> 00:45:34.830
there so that's tough.
It's been a big problem.

00:45:34.830 --> 00:45:38.069
And sometimes I went to, like, Morocco and
it was winter and we got

00:45:38.069 --> 00:45:40.130
hosed.
It was bad weather for three weeks and somebody

00:45:40.130 --> 00:45:42.619
said, you know, it's
snowing in, I don't know, in Whatchamacallit.

00:45:42.619 --> 00:45:45.650
I said, well, where in the hell is Whatchamacallit?
Gad zukes.

00:45:45.650 --> 00:45:47.980
There was snow there on the palm trees.
It was fantastic.

00:45:47.980 --> 00:45:59.130
We had, you know, one good day in three weeks.
It's like that sometimes.

00:45:59.130 --> 00:46:00.130
It's tough.
Any other questions in.

00:46:00.130 --> 00:46:03.200
&gt;&gt; Umm, is there any chance or possiblity
to make some of those great

00:46:03.200 --> 00:46:05.400
pictures available for Google Earth?

00:46:05.400 --> 00:46:09.950
George Steinmetz: Yeah.
Actually, I'm working on making a layer and,

00:46:09.950 --> 00:46:12.311
uh, things that
will -- gonna be plugged into Google Earth.

00:46:12.311 --> 00:46:19.099
So -- Google Earth it's been an amazing, uh,
resource for me and

00:46:19.099 --> 00:46:21.710
'cause it's just the whole world, and it's
searchable.

00:46:21.710 --> 00:46:25.200
And you can look at it in time.
I had a problem when I first started using

00:46:25.200 --> 00:46:27.880
Google Earth when it was in
its infancy and I'd look at an area and it

00:46:27.880 --> 00:46:29.180
didn't tell me what date
the picture was taken in.

00:46:29.180 --> 00:46:33.670
So I'd try and go there and the picture was
taken in the winter and I

00:46:33.670 --> 00:46:36.079
was going there in the summer and the pictures
didn't match up.

00:46:36.079 --> 00:46:37.720
And now it's just there's so much more information
there.

00:46:37.720 --> 00:46:40.230
It's a really amazing resource so I'm happy
to give something back.

00:46:40.230 --> 00:46:44.650
Well, thank you all for coming.

00:46:44.650 --> 00:46:45.980
&gt;&gt; [Applause]

